post_text:
Department of Health & Human Services School Re-Opening Guidance

Please take a look at StrongSchoolsNC: Public Health Toolkit (K-12) to read about the health and safety requirements directly from the Department of Health & Human Services (DHHS). This document will be helpful in informing our stakeholders what types of health and safety procedures schools will be taking to ensure the health & safety of our students and staff. This toolkit lists the specific requirements that schools need to implement.

In addition to the StrongSchoolsNC Toolkit, DHHS has also developed very specific protocols for what school staff need to do if an individual is symptom-positive or has contracted COVID-19.

Links to the documents (in English and Spanish), as well as an FAQ on the guidance, can be found on our district webpage @ https://www.tyrrell.k12.nc.us/DHHSGuidance/

Good afternoon friends and families of Columbia High School,

Our graduation will take place this evening starting at 5:30PM. You can find all the details, including links to our livestream feed beginning at 5:00PM, and individual pre-recorded videos of all speakers on our CHS webpage, under “School Information, Graduation 2020” or at https://chs.tyrrell.k12.nc.us/graduation2020/.

Thank you.

shared_text:
Columbia High School
May 3 at 3:34 PM ·

Can anyone help us make contact with anyone with connections to any Tyrrell High School students from 1959? *See screenshot of the PM received by CHS.

Here's a little history on the schools of Tyrrell County:

Tyrrell Elementary School, home of the Bulldogs, was not always an elementary school. Built in the early 1950’s, Tyrrell Elementary was originally named Tyrrell High School and served as the segregation school for blacks in K-12. It wasn’t until the 1969-1970 school year, that the building became renamed Tyrrell Elementary and served as an integrated school for 1st - 6th grade. A year later, Kindergarten was added to Tyrrell Elementary. Around the 1993-1994 school year, a new addition was built onto Tyrrell Elementary and 6th grade was moved to the middle school campus across the highway.

post_text:
April is Child Abuse Prevention Month, a time to act collectively to raise awareness and empower people across the nation to play a role in making great childhoods happen. And our efforts to raise awareness and engagement and impact positive change this year are as vital as ever.

The outbreak of the coronavirus, also known as COVID-19, has changed our world dramatically—and rapidly. Although the risk to our children’s physical health from the outbreak itself appears to be low…the risk to our nation’s children for experiencing child abuse and neglect in times of extreme stress and uncertainty is actually quite high.

Throughout this crucial Child Abuse Prevention Month, we’re reinforcing the message that “Everyone can make great childhoods happen—especially you, especially now!”

Read more at Prevent Child Abuse North Carolina @ https://www.preventchildabusenc.org/

UPDATE: Tyrrell County Schools will be CLOSED, Friday, February 14, 2020

post_text:
This is a message from Oliver A. Holley, Superintendent of Tyrrell County Schools.

We have been made aware of the possible threats that are circulating on social media. We are currently working with local law enforcement to address these concerns.

The district has implemented our safety policy and procedures as we continue to monitor the situation.

We will continue to update you as we get additional developments.

Thank you for your trust in our district as we will continue to make sure we provide a safe learning environment for all staff, students and community members.

post_text:
Good evening,

Tyrrell County has recently been placed under a Tornado Watch until 7pm this evening.

"What is the difference between a Tornado Watch and a Tornado Warning issued by the National Weather Service?
https://www.weather.gov/safety/tornado-ww

https://forecast.weather.gov/showsigwx.php?warnzone=NCZ015&warncounty=NCC139&firewxzone=NCZ015&local_place1=Elizabeth%20City%20NC&product1=Tornado+Watch&lat=36.2953&lon=-76.2353#.XjxVYzJKiUk

As a precaution we are canceling all after school activities, including Parks and Recreations for today, February 6, 2020.

We will continue to monitor area weather alerts for the remainder of the evening and into the morning hours.

I ask that teachers and staff secure your classrooms/buildings and prepare to exit campus this evening once students are safely off campus.

Thank you and please feel free to contact me if you have any questions or concerns.

Oliver A. Holley
Superintendent
Tyrrell County Schools

post_text:
Did you know that Columbia High School has a weather station?

A weather station is a device that collects data related to the weather and environment using many different sensors.
Weather stations sensors may include a thermometer to take temperature readings, a barometer to measure the pressure in the atmosphere, as well as other sensors to measure rain, wind, humidity and more.

You can check it out here --> https://www.weatherlink.com/embeddablePage/show/3a77f77095b348d18ce06b065d257192/fullscreen

Or find a link on the CHS Science page or the TCS district page under "Our District."

post_text:
In addition to the previously announced closures, the district will also be closed on Friday, September 6th, 2019.

Again, Tyrrell County Schools will now be closed Wednesday, September 4th - Friday, September 6th, 2019.

All athletic and Parks and Recreation activities are cancelled until further notice.

We ask that you monitor our school web pages, social media, WITN and other local/regional networks for the most recent information and closure updates.

In order to ensure the safety and security of the families of Tyrrell County Schools, we ask that you make preparations for this weather event.
You can find hurricane preparedness tips and information at www.readync.org and updated local weather forecasts from the National Weather Service at www.weather.gov/mhx.

Thank you and be safe!

post_text: The staff at the Tyrrell County Department of Public Safety donated school supplies to Tyrrell County Schools on Wednesday, August 28, 2019. Ms. Renee Mangum, Administrative Assistant to Warden Caroline Riddick-Taylor delivered the supplies to central office. Superintendent Oliver A. Holley accepted the donation on behalf of Tyrrell County Schools. Thank you DPS for your continued support to our district.

Registration - Dolly Parton's Imagination Library | Smart Start & The North Carolina Partnership for Children

Karen Clough - Tyrrell County Board of Education
August 20, 2019 at 12:45 PM ·

Calling all families with children under the age of 5:

There is a free resource in our community, the Dolly Parton imagination Library, that allows you to get a book once a month for your child.

The books are great!

Here is a link to register http://www.smartstart.org/dolly-partons-imagination-library/registration-dolly-partons-imagination-library/

or call the Tyrrell-Washington Partnership for Children 252-793-5437

Please Share - Let's get every child in Tyrrell County to develop a love of reading early!
